    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Lowering the Global Thermostat</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Michael Radkowsky letter responds to Bob Herbert's July 17 column on global warming; suggests planting a tree, even in New York City, to help slow global warming</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In addition to the ways Bob Herbert offers ''to move from our pollution-choked present'' (column, July 17), why not plant trees on a large scale, starting right here in New York City?</p>
        <p>Trees consume carbon dioxide and airborne pollutants. The more there are, the better they can do this essential work.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In addition to the ways Bob Herbert offers ''to move from our pollution-choked present'' (column, July 17), why not plant trees on a large scale, starting right here in New York City?</p>
        <p>Trees consume carbon dioxide and airborne pollutants. The more there are, the better they can do this essential work.</p>
        <p>Looking out my window onto Amsterdam Avenue, I see just one struggling tree on a block that suffers a parade of cars, day and night. Let's  plant more trees and show the world how simple remedies can play a big role in preserving life on earth.</p>
        <p>MICHAEL RADKOWSKY  New York, July 17, 2000</p>
      </block>
